question:
\textbf{If I toss a fair coin 5000 times} 

Options:
A. \textbf{and I get anything other than 2500 heads, then something is wrong with the way I flip coins.} 
B. \textbf{the proportion of heads will be close to 0.5} 
C. \textbf{a run of 10 heads in a row will increase the probability of getting a run of 10 tails in a row.} 
D. \textbf{the proportion of heads in these tosses is a parameter} 
E. \textbf{the proportion of heads will be close to 50.}

\textbf{According to data from the United States Elections Project, only 36 percent of eligible voters voted in the 2014 elections. For random samples of size 40, which of the following best describes the sampling distribution of pˆ, the sample proportion of people who voted in the 2014 elections?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{The sampling distribution is skewed to the left, with mean 0.36 and standard deviation 0.076.} 
B. \textbf{The sampling distribution is skewed to the right, with mean 0.64 and standard deviation 0.006.~} 
C. \textbf{The sampling distribution is approximately normal, with mean 0.36 and standard deviation 0.076.~} 
D. \textbf{The sampling distribution is approximately normal, with mean 0.36 and standard deviation 0.006.~} 
E. \textbf{The sampling distribution is approximately normal,with mean 0.64 and standard deviation 0.076.~}

\textbf{Sean and Evan are college roommates who have part-time jobs as servers in restaurants. The distribution of Sean's weekly income is approximately normal with mean $\textbackslash$225$ and standard deviation $\textbackslash$25$. The distribution of Evan's weekly income is approximately normal with mean $\textbackslash$240$ and standard deviation $15. Assuming their weekly incomes are independent of each other, which of the following is closest to the probability that Sean will have a greater income than Evan in a randomly selected week?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{0.067} 
B. \textbf{0.159} 
C. \textbf{0.227} 
D. \textbf{0.303} 
E. \textbf{0.354}

\textbf{The height and age of each child in a random sample of children was recorded. The value of the correlation coefficient between height and age for the children in the sample was 0.8. Based on the least-squares regression line created from the data to predict the height of a child based on age, which of the following is a correct statement?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{~On average, the height of a child is 80\% of the age of the child.} 
B. \textbf{The least-squares regression line of height versus age will have a slope of 0.8.} 
C. \textbf{The proportion of the variation in height that is explained by a regression on age is 0.64.~} 
D. \textbf{The least-squares regression line will correctly predict height based on age 80\% of the time.} 
E. \textbf{The least-squares regression line will correctly predict height based on age 64\% of the time.}

\textbf{A stationery store owner calculated the mean and median price of all types of pen: 5 and 3, respectively. He plans to have a 20\% off sale. What are the new mean and median of pens in that store?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{mean: 4; median: 2.4} 
B. \textbf{mean: 5; median: 2.4} 
C. \textbf{~mean: 4; median: 3} 
D. \textbf{~mean: 5; median: 3} 
E. \textbf{mean: 2.4; median: 4}

\textbf{A statistical test involves the following null and alternative hypotheses.~}  \textbf{H0: $\mu$ = 64}  \textbf{Ha: $\mu$ \textgreater{} 64}  \textbf{Which of the following describes a Type II error?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{Failing to reject the null hypothesis when the population mean is 64} 
B. \textbf{Failing to reject the null hypothesis when the population mean is greater than 64} 
C. \textbf{Rejecting the null hypothesis when the population mean is 64} 
D. \textbf{Rejecting the null hypothesis when the population mean is greater than 64} 
E. \textbf{Failing to reject the null hypothesis when the p-value is less than the significance level}

\textbf{Which of the following events are independent?}  \textbf{P(A) = 0.7, P(B) = 0.2, P(C) = 0.1, P(B\textbar A) = 0.5, P(B\textbar C) = 0.2, P(A∩C) = 0.0} 

Options:
A. \textbf{A and B only} 
B. \textbf{A and C only} 
C. \textbf{A, B, and C} 
D. \textbf{B and C only} 
E. \textbf{None are independent}

\textbf{Recently you learned that the probability of getting a critical hit on an attack in your favorite game is 15\%. You've noticed that you do 20 attacks per fight. You're interested in figuring out how likely it is that you would get 5 critical hits during a fight. Which of the following distributions should you use to answer this question?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{A binomial distribution with p = 0.15 and n = 20} 
B. \textbf{A binomial distribution with p = 0.2 and n = 15} 
C. \textbf{A geometric distribution with p = 0.15} 
D. \textbf{A geometric distribution with p = 0.2} 
E. \textbf{A cumulative geometric distribution with p = 0.15}

\textbf{Which of the following data sets has the largest standard deviation?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{{100, 101, 102, 103, 104}} 
B. \textbf{{1000.3, 999.56, 1000.49, 1000, 998.32}} 
C. \textbf{{1, 1, 1, 1, 1}} 
D. \textbf{{5, 10, 15, 20, 25}} 
E. \textbf{{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}}

\textbf{Events D and E are independent, with P(D) = 0.6 and P(D and E) = 0.18. Which of the following is true?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{P(E) = 0.12} 
B. \textbf{P(E) = 0.4} 
C. \textbf{P(D or E) = 0.28} 
D. \textbf{P(D or E) = 0.72} 
E. \textbf{P(D or E) = 0.9}

\textbf{Scientists estimate that the distribution of the life span of the Galápagos Islands giant tortoise is approximately normal with mean 100 years and standard deviation 15 years. Based on the estimate, which of the following is closest to the age of a Galápagos Islands giant tortoise at the 90th percentile of the distribution?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{80 years} 
B. \textbf{115 years} 
C. \textbf{120 years} 
D. \textbf{125 years} 
E. \textbf{130 years}

\textbf{From a random sample of 1,005 adults in the United States, it was found that 32 percent own an e-reader. Which of the following is the appropriate 90 percent confidence interval to estimate the proportion of all adults in the United States who own an e-reader?~} 

Options:
A. \textbf{$0.32 \pm 1.960(\frac{(0.32)(0.68)}{\sqrt{1,005}})$} 
B. \textbf{$0.32 \pm 1.645(\frac{(0.32)(0.68)}{\sqrt{1,005}})$} 
C. \textbf{$0.32 \pm 2.575\sqrt{(\frac{(0.32)(0.68)}{1,005})}$} 
D. \textbf{$0.32 \pm 1.960\sqrt{(\frac{(0.32)(0.68)}{1,005})}$} 
E. \textbf{$0.32 \pm 1.645\sqrt{(\frac{(0.32)(0.68)}{1,005})}$}

\textbf{If P(A) = 0.34 and P(A or B) = 0.71, which of the following is false?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{P(B) = 0.37 , if A and B are mutually exclusive.} 
B. \textbf{P(B) = 0.561, if A and B are independent.} 
C. \textbf{P(B) cannot be determined if A and B are neither mutually exclusive nor independent.} 
D. \textbf{P(A and B) = 0.191 , if A and B are independent.} 
E. \textbf{P(A\textbar B) = 0.34 , if A and B are mutually exclusive.}

\textbf{A basketball player makes 160 out of 200 free throws. We would estimate the probability that the player makes his next free throw to be heads the fourth time.} 

Options:
A. \textbf{0.15} 
B. \textbf{0.50; either he makes it or he doesn't} 
C. \textbf{0.80} 
D. \textbf{1.2} 
E. $$80$$

\textbf{At a certain restaurant, the distribution of wait times between ordering a meal and receiving the meal has mean 11.4 minutes and standard deviation 2.6 minutes. The restaurant manager wants to find the probability that the mean wait time will be greater than 12.0 minutes for a random sample of 84 customers. Assuming the wait times among customers are independent, which of the following describes the sampling distribution of the sample mean wait time for random samples of size 84 ?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{~Approximately normal with mean 11.4 minutes and standard deviation 2.6 minutes} 
B. \textbf{~Approximately normal with mean 11.4 minutes and standard deviation $\frac{2.6}{\sqrt{84}}$ minute~} 
C. \textbf{Approximately normal with mean 12.0 minutes and standard deviation 2.6 minutes} 
D. \textbf{Binomial with mean 84(0.41) minutes and standard deviation 84(0.41)(0.59) minutes~} 
E. \textbf{Binomial with mean 84(0.5) minutes and standard deviation 84(0.5)(0.5) minutes}

\textbf{A news organization conducted a survey about preferred methods for obtaining the news. A random sample of 1,605 adults living in a certain state was selected, and 16.2 percent of the adults in the sample reported that television was their preferred method. Which of the following is an appropriate margin of error for a 90 percent confidence interval to estimate the population proportion of all adults living in the state who would report that television is their preferred method for obtaining the news?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{$1.645 \sqrt{\frac{(0.162)(1-0.162)}{1605}}$} 
B. \textbf{$1.645 \sqrt{\frac{(0.5)(1-0.5)}{1605}}$} 
C. \textbf{$1.96 \sqrt{\frac{(0.162)(1-0.162)}{1605}}$} 
D. \textbf{$1.96 \sqrt{\frac{(0.5)(1-0.5)}{1605}}$} 
E. \textbf{$1.83 \sqrt{\frac{(0.162)(1-0.162)}{1605}}$}

\textbf{High school students from track teams in the state participated in a training program to improve running times. Before the training, the mean running time for the students to run a mile was 402 seconds with standard deviation 40 seconds. After completing the program, the mean running time for the students to run a mile was 368 seconds with standard deviation 30 seconds. Let X represent the running time of a randomly selected student before training, and let Y represent the running time of the same student after training. Which of the following is true about the distribution of X - Y ?} 

Options:
A. \textbf{The variables X and Y are independent; therefore, the mean is 34 seconds and the standard deviation is 10 seconds.} 
B. \textbf{~The variables X and Y are independent; therefore, the mean is 34 seconds and the standard deviation is 50 seconds.} 
C. \textbf{The variables X and Y are not independent; therefore, the standard deviation is 50 seconds and the mean cannot be determined with the information given.} 
D. \textbf{The variables X and Y are not independent; therefore, the mean is 34 seconds and the standard deviation cannot be determined with the information given.} 
E. \textbf{The variables X and Y are not independent; therefore, neither the mean nor the standard deviation can be determined with the information given.}

David went to watch $Spider Man$ at the cinema on June $25$\textsuperscript{th}. The movie started at $6 : 32$ P.M. and finished at $7 : 54$ P.M.. On the same day, Mary needed to go abroad by plane. The plane took off at $11 : 40$ P.M., and the time she spent on plane was $2$ hours and $11$ minutes longer than that David spent at the cinema. When would Mary get off the plane? 

Options:
A. $3 : 23$ P.M. on June $25$\textsuperscript{th} 
B. $3 : 13$ A.M. on June $25$\textsuperscript{th} 
C. $3 : 13$ P.M. on June $26$\textsuperscript{th} 
D. $3 : 13$ A.M. on June $26$\textsuperscript{th} 
E. $3 : 23$ A.M. on June $26$\textsuperscript{th}

Cecilia and her dad are climbing stairs from the first floor. They start at the same time, and each of them keeps her or his speed of climbing unchanged. When Cecilia arrives at the third floor, her dad arrives at the fifth floor. When Cecilia arrives at the eighth floor, which floor does her dad arrive at? 

Options:
A. $$14$$\textsuperscript{th} 
B. $$15$$\textsuperscript{th} 
C. $$10$$\textsuperscript{th} 
D. $$13$$\textsuperscript{th} 
E. $$16$$\textsuperscript{th}

